|{{refn|group=note|name=Awarded|The final match originally finished 1–0 for Senegal after [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]]. On 17 March 2026, the CAF Appeal Board ruled that Senegal had forfeited the match for temporarily refusing to play and leaving the pitch in protest of a refereeing decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/ce949glzzglo |title=Morocco awarded Afcon title after CAF overturns result |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=17 March 2026 |access-date=17 March 2026 |archive-date=17 March 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260317222030/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/ce949glzzglo |url-status=live }}</ref> Pursuant to articles 82 and 84 of the competition regulations, the final was awarded as a 3–0 win for Morocco, thereby retroactively declaring them as 2025 Africa Cup of Nations champions and stripping Senegal of the title.<ref name="CAF appeal">{{cite web |url=https://www.cafonline.com/news/caf-appeal-board-media-statement/ |title=CAF Appeal Board Media Statement |publisher=[[Confederation of African Football]] |date=17 March 2026 |access-date=17 March 2026|archive-date=17 March 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260317220033/http://web.archive.org/screenshot/https://www.cafonline.com/news/caf-appeal-board-media-statement/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The following day, the [[Senegalese Football Federation]] announced it would appeal the decision to the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]].<ref name="Senegal appeal">{{cite web |url=https://fsfoot.sn/affaire-decision-jury-dappel-de-la-caf/ |title=Affaire décision Jury d'appel de la CAF |trans-title=CAF Appeal Board Decision |publisher=[[Senegalese Football Federation]] |date=18 March 2026 |access-date=18 March 2026 |language=fr}}</ref>}}<s>[[2025 Africa Cup of Nations final]]</s>
